# Agent Identity and Terminology Enforcement

This rule is always applied. It standardizes agent identity and forbids hierarchical concepts in naming, data models, events, and UI logic.

## Prohibited Concepts (Hard Ban)
- "main agent", "mainAgent", `mainAgentId`
- "sub-agent", "parent-agent", "child-agent"
- "primary/secondary agent", "master/slave" and any hierarchy-implying naming

## Approved Terminology
- "agent" (the only standard term)
- "agent instance" or "agent replica" when referring to a specific occurrence
- Identifiers: `agent_0`, `agent_1`, ...
- Variables: `agentId`, `agentNumber`, `agentNodeId`

## Implementation Requirements
- Do not compute, store, or pass any field that implies hierarchy among agents (e.g., `mainAgentId`).
- Execution/UI logic MUST NOT rely on a special agent role. All agents share the same lifecycle and event semantics.
- Layouts and connections MUST be derived purely from events and edges, not from a designated "main" agent.
- Event constants ownership and prefixes must be respected; no hardcoded strings.

## Migration and Validation
- Replace any existing usages of `mainAgentId` or similar with architecture-appropriate context, e.g., `rootExecutionId`, `parentExecutionId`, `executionPath` (only if truly needed for execution context, not hierarchy).
- Remove comments or logs that imply hierarchy among agents.
- UI derivations (grouping, ordering) must be based on graph edges and timestamps, not special agent roles.

## Code Review Checklist
- No occurrences of: `mainAgentId`, `mainAgent`, `subAgent`, `parentAgent`, `childAgent`.
- Graph building does not assume a privileged agent.
- Event names use declarative constants with correct ownership/prefix.
- Any legacy references are refactored to domain-neutral context.

